name: Test Driven Development in Django
description: Adam Haney will be discussing approaches for test driven development in Django. This includes techniques for testing models, forms, form wizards, views and templates. We'll also discuss Python's Mock library and how mocking and stubbing can be used to isolate test cases.

name: Using knowledge systems to automatically address system problems
description: Josh Marlow has been working on 'Django Narrative' a system that has the ability to identify issues as they arise and help developers and support staff to diagnose problems that are data or system related.

name: Developing applications in a Vagrant environment
description: Micah Hausler will be explaining how to use Vagrant for local development that mimics a production environment</p>

name: Thinking in Objects
description: Anthony Blardo will be going over his philosophy for creating good object oriented code. Instead of simply covering basic OO concepts this talk discusses a state of mind for development.

name: An overview of Angular.js
description: Roger Maarfi will be presenting an introduction to the Angular.js framework.

name: EMCAScript 6 and the future of Javascript w/ Jeffery McRiffey
Human First Web Design w/ Daniel Ryan
Using IPython Notebook to analyze Django model Data w/ Adam Haney
An introduction to grails w/ Jared Menard
Unity 3D w/ Rodger Maarfi
An Introduction to Cryptography for Programmers w/ Micah Hausler
Refactoring legacy code bases for fun and profit w/ Chris Keathley
Intro to Augmented Reality using the Metaio SDK, with Reed "Wreck It" Tomlinson
Handling Time Zones and Recurrences like a Boss in Python/Django w/ Wes Kendall
description: Doing datetime manipulation in Python can be a very tedious task, especially across different time zones and daylight savings time boundaries. This talk summarizes a new open-source library called "Fleming" that aids in doing datetime manipulation across timezones. It also talks about "Django Localized Recurrence", another new open-source library for scheduling recurrences of events based on a time zone. The talk also gives a basic introduction to pytz in Python and some of the ways that Django handles time zones.

name: How economics effects developers w/ Rodger Maarfi
An Introduction to Adaptive Design w/ Aaron Gustafson
description:
For years, designers and developers have griped about the difficulties they encountered in supporting the numerous desktop browsers out there, but mobile is even more fragmented. Phones, tablets, media players, video game systems—each device (and in some cases each browser on each device) has its own dimensions, quirks and capabilities. It can make your brain hurt just thinking about it.

Thankfully, going mobile doesn’t have to be a painful experience. In this session, Aaron Gustafson will introduce you to the concept of progressive enhancement and demonstrate why it is the way forward for web design, especially on mobile devices. In the course of his talk, he’ll walk you through progressive enhancement’s layered approach and show you how the latest techniques—mobile first, responsive design, and adaptive UI—fit in to the process.

name: Continuous Integration and Deployment @Bellhops w/ Adam Haney
description: Several developers have asked about tools and process for bringing continuous integration into their organization. I'd love to give an overview of how Bellhops does continuous integration and deployment and also highlight tools that are available.

name: Writing fast unit tests w/ Chris Keathley
Concurrency in Go w/ Adam Jimerson
Olfactory Refactoring part 1 w/ Anthony Blardo
Olfactory Refactoring part 2 w/ Anthony Blardo
An Introduction to Angular.js w/ Chris Keathley
.NET trolling - why Microsoft is worth looking at w/ Rodger Maarfi

name: Open Source Map Making w/ Jason Denizac
UTC Computer Science and Engineering Department Q&A
description: Dr. Joseph Kizza is going to talk to us about the UTC CS department. This is a great chance for us to give him feedback on their program-- what we wished we had learned in college, what we think Chattanooga needs right now, compliments, complaints, etc. Come give some constructive feedback, and help build UTC's program into the Dev Wizard Factory that Chattanooga needs!

name: Net Neutrality with Chris Riley, Mozilla's Senior Policy Engineer
description: Chris Riley from Mozilla is going to tell us about the issue of Net Neutrality- what it is, how it's being threatened, and what can be done. This talk is not limited to devs! Bring anyone who may have an interest in the subject. Chris will be joining us via videochat.

name: Activism, Hacking and the Chinese web w/ Brett Wise
An introduction to meteor.js w/ Andrew McPherson
Open Data: What is it anyway? w/ Sean Brewer
description: The City of Chattanooga recently proposed an open data initiative. I will explain open data and how you can participate in the open data movement.

name: An introduction to static analysis w/ Adam Haney
Photoshop for developers w/ Rodger Maarfi
Set up an immutable server in 10 minutes using Ansible w/ Ryan Lelek
From Queues to Caches: Redis Design patterns w/ Chris Keathley
description: Redis is a key value store that I've used in a lot of different use cases. I thought it would be fun to look over those use cases and discuss common design patterns in Redis.

name: OpenStreetMap 101
description: What's OpenStreetMap? How is it useful? What can I do with it? Come learn about all of these things!

name: Useful, Usable & Desirable: Designing for People w/ Jessica Ivins
description:
"It needs to be easy to use." We've heard this many times before from stakeholders, clients, and colleagues. But how do you go about making a website—or any product or service—easy to use? While there are plenty of industry leaders, books, articles, and best practices to learn from, what matters is context. For whom are you designing? What is this person's goals, motivations, and pain points? What is he or she trying to accomplish? Good design solves real problems. It doesn't just decorate. How can you design to solve real problems for real people?

This session will explore the fundamentals of user experience. We'll explore industry best practices and examples of websites that solve real problems for real people. There are many tools and disciplines within user experience, from content strategy to information architecture to user research. By understanding these tools and when to use them, and by understanding the context of each design problem we are faced with, we can begin to understand how to utilize design thinking and creating user experiences that are useful, usable, and desirable.

name: Like webscale but over 9000: Introduction to elixir and erlang
description: Erlang has been behind some of the most reliable systems ever built.  Elixir is a new language that seeks to combine that same performance with the power of a dynamic language.  In this talk we'll go over the basics of Elixir, functional concepts, and demonstrate how easy it is to build large scale, reliable systems on the Erlang VM.

name: Speed Matters: Profiling Server Side Code w/ Wil Wade
How not to be a Git w/ Adam Jimerson
description: So you know the basics of Git, but there is so much more that just creating repositories, adding and committing changes, and pushing and pulling changes to remote repositories. Through this session I hope to teach you some tips and tricks as well as best practices to help you get the most of out Git and work better as a team.

name: Lightning Talks!
description: Playing with something new?  Just solved an interesting problem?  Have some unsolved question?  You should give a lightning talk!  You'll have 5 minutes to talk about something that you think is interesting.

name: Good Migrations: SQL performance w/ Rodger Maarfi
description: Indices, schemas, and how to access your data are all on the table.

name: Deathmatch2D: Evolutionary Algorithms for Creative Coding w/ Alex Cruikshank
Cluster Computing with Clojure and Mesos w/ Ben Weaver
description: Mesos is an open source cluster manager modeled after Google’s Omega for building distributed systems. We’ll take a simple tour and see how to build a simple Clojure framework that can run Mesos tasks.

description: Mesos is an open source cluster manager modeled after Google’s Omega for building distributed systems. We’ll take a simple tour and see how to build a simple Clojure framework that can run Mesos tasks.

description: As is our custom we want to give people a chance to speak on a topic that they are just learning about, a problem they recently had to solve, or anything else you think is interesting. If you haven't spoken before then this is a great way to test topics or to research something you want to know more about.

description: Micah has been using Docker for a while now and is going to give us all the run down.

name: Docker Part 2 w/ Micah Hausler
description: More Docker!!!

name: Getting Sass-y w/ Jordan Isip
description:
How to take advantage of Sass/Less CSS pre-processors to stay sane while building out designs.  

How to get started, some best practices, and common mistakes. Further reading - Sass: http://sass-lang.com . Less: http://lesscss.org/

name: Falling in Love with Forms w/ Aaron Gustafson
description:
In this session, we will explore forms from top to bottom, examining how they work and how their components can be incorporated with other elements to maximize accessibility, improve semantics, and allow for more flexible styling. You’ll get to see the complete picture with forms, including:


* new HTML5 field types;

* validation, error messages & formatting hints;

* how to mark up and style forms for the greatest flexibility in responsive designs; and

* best practices for enhancing forms with JavaScript.

name: So long, jQuery, and thanks for all the fish! w/ Matt Turnure
description: If you can't make this event, catch it streaming here: https://plus.google.com/b/103401260409601780643/events/cr4c6cb96aartv677su6mb6jkn8

name: Telling local stories with data viz and d3.js w/ Mary Helen Miller
description:
D3.js is a javascript library, created by a developer at the New York Times. It’s a powerful tool for manipulating the document object model and creating beautiful data visualizations, in journalism and beyond.

Come learn about how D3 can be used. I’ll show you a range of projects that use D3, including a few projects that I’ve created for the Chattanooga Times Free Press. We’ll talk about how data visualizations can help us ask better questions and tell better stories about our community.

Remember if you can't make it this  week, you can catch it on YouTube here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mk0XwRqpitU

name: Civic User Testing with Tyler Yount
description:
Tyler will tell us about how the Civic User Testing group helps civic initiatives verify efficacy and user experience.

This will be on the 4th Floor of the Public Library as part of CityCampCha, if you are just attending the talk you can simply RSVP here as you would normally for lunch, however, you should check all of the great content that will be at CityCampCha here: https://citycampcha.com/

name: Finding happiness in Turing completeness w/ Chris Keathley
description: A whirlwind tour of Touring equivalence, language design, and finding happiness in programming.

name: Hanging up on Callbacks: Generators in ES6 w/ Erin Swenson-Healey
description:
While the JavaScript event loop and asynchronous callbacks provide a powerful, easy-to-understand concurrency model - writing applications in continuation-passing style introduces problems of legibility, exception management, and composability. With the introduction of generators in the ECMAScript 6 Draft Specification, programmers can continue to leverage the power of the single-threaded event loop while writing expressive, simple code in a direct, top-down style.

-- Bio

After a stint in Honduras teaching web development with the Peace Corps, Erin landed in Santa Monica where he now writes and codes for Carbon Five. He loves Seattle, arguing with software developers, and soccer (among other things).

name: Introduction To Livecoding With Overtone and Clojure w/ Sean Brewer
description: Livecoding as a musical and visual artform has been slowly progressing into the mainstream. I will show you how to get started with livecoding using Overtone and Emacs Live. Then, using algorithmic techniques and basic music theory, I will build a piece of music during the presentation.

name: The 12 Factor App; what does it mean, and why should I care? w/ Adam Jimerson
description: The 12 Factor app is a modern way of building scalable web applications popularized by Heroku and other companies. Adam is going to break down this information and show us how to write apps that conform to the 12 factors.

name: Every Coder’s Dirty Secret: Burnout w/ Wil Wade
description: Every job suffers from burnout, but programmers suffering from burnout can produce poor code causing more problems than we solve. Severe burnout leads to job and even career changes. We will talk about burnout identification, prevention, and recovery.

name: Candidate Centered Recruiting w/ Ben Schnell
description: How programmers, hiring-managers and recruiters can collaborate for best results

name: Building assets with Gulp w/ Ustin Zarubin
description: Gulp is becoming an increasingly popular way to build client side assets.  Ustin is going to give us an overview of how to get started using it in production.

name: Multirotor Madness: Intro to Quadcopters w/ Anthony Blardo
description: It's Quadcopters!!! Learn how they work and how to get started.

name: Lightning Talks!!!
description:
Its time again for lightning talks.

If you have a fun idea, niche piece of tech, clever hack, or anything in between we would love to hear about it.

name: Web asset performance and optimization w/ Brett Wise and Chris Keathley
description: Join us for a talk and discussion on ways that we can optimize our assets and pages. We'll discuss some tried and true techniques as well as some cutting edge tech.

name: Building Sprite-based 2D Games in React w/ Andrew McPherson
description: React is a javascript framework built by facebook to create a reactive and consistent web experience. But it really isn’t difficult to use it to also create real-time and sprite-based web games! Join us to learn more about prototyping a game using React!

name: Values Driven Development w/ Alan Stevens
description:
How we develop and ship software expresses the values of our team, business & users. Many teams can’t state their driving values. The process of outlining a shared set of values can lead to enhanced team identity and help align development efforts. The inverse of this process is looking at what the team has done historically and working backward from that to find the implicit values that have driven team behavior. If we study how we spend time, money and energy, we can cultivate a picture of our values in practice. There will be a gap or dissonance between our self professed values and those visible to others from our actions. Embracing this dissonance can drive out more clarity and coherence in our future efforts.


Attendees will leave with strategies for defining a set of shared values across a team as well as ways to find the values that have driven our behavior historically.

name: Chattanooga Innovation District Two-Way Briefing

description:

AudiencePoint, the company Paul works for, pinpoints the best time to connect with each individual in a given e-mail list by leveraging historical information and parsing out when each subscriber is most like to be online which improves deliverability, open and click through rates, and conversions.

Paul brings a wealth of knowledge in this area so bring your questions.

name: How to Survive your First Hackathon
description:
Join us to learn how to survive a hackathon, and while you're at it, make something cool! Andrew McPherson will share his experiences from his otherwise unhealthy addiction to hackathons.

You can expect to hear why you should be attending more hackathons, what you can do to succeed at hackathons, and where you can get involved with hackathons in the area.

name: Building Quantum Pilot: iOS Game Development

QP is going to be talking to us about the game he built, Quantum Pilot. 

You can see the game trailer here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JBaYS1WP5dU

name: Web Application Security and You: Intro to OWASP and Penetration Testing
description:
Micah is a systems engineer at Ambition.  He's going to be taking us through each of the OWASP top 10 and outlining how we can check our own sites for vulnerabilities. 

Catch Micah on Github and come prepared to ask questions.

See you all there!

name: Introduction to Graph Databases
description:
Hey everyone. We're most excited to have Tim coming to us with a talk on graph databases. 

Tim is a developer at AudiencePoint where he works on everything from backend services, C# being the language of choice, to devops, to web apps. 

================

Before he hops on the annoucement here to give a quick rundown of his topic we want to give a shout out to Open Table and Society of Work. Both of them have been supporting our community for a while. Wouldn't be able to do it without you all!

================

And now a brief intro from our speaker: 

In many of the information models we have today, relationships between entities are super important. 

"What items were purchased by at least 3 or more of my friends?" 

"Which flights went from JFK to SFO through DFW on Jan 8th?" 

Turns out relational databases are not very efficient in answering these kinds of questions. Enter Graph databases. 

Graph databases store connections as first class citizens so they can answer complex queries on highly connected data more efficiently than a relational database can. 

In this talk, I'll introduced Graph databases (Neo4j in particular), talk about what makes them different from an RDBMS or Key-Value store and learn how to get started with the Cypher query language.

================

Check out our Humans of Chadev series on our new Instagram.

================

name: Zen and the Art of Simple Software: the Unix Philosophy - Stephen Spalding
description: Stephen Spalding of OpenTable will take us back to a simpler time before the Internet, Restful frameworks, and Javascript. The Unix Philosophy was born in the 60s and 70s, and encouraged short, simple, clear, modular, and extensible code. Though times have changed, this philosophy continues to find relevance today.

name: Intro to Data Science in Python - Jeff McGhee
description:
The "Intro to Data Science in Python" tutorial will cover popular Python packages and tools for data science.  The main purpose is to inform attendees of the existence of these tools and give a small demo of their capabilities.  The presentation will begin with raw .csv data and end with informative visualizations generated using statistics and some light machine learning.

Jeff McGehee moved towards Data Science and Machine Learning from a background in Mechanical Engineering.  His interest in ML came about when investigating novel solutions for optimal control of hybrid vehicles in graduate school at Tennessee Tech University.  He currently works for a local startup, Variable Inc., and is enrolled in Georgia Tech's Online Masters of Science in Computer Science program (OMSCS) with a focus in Machine Learning.  He maintains a blog with all of his projects at www.nooganeer.com/his

name: 7 Rules for Creating Gorgeous UI
description:
Hey Chadevs! This weeks talk is brought to you by Carbon Five and we have Erik Kennedy bringing us a talk on pragmatic rules for creating gorgeous UI.

You may have read his series of articles that were passed around quite extensively in our circles.

https://medium.com/@erikdkennedy/7-rules-for-creating-gorgeous-ui-part-1-559d4e805cda


https://medium.com/@erikdkennedy/7-rules-for-creating-gorgeous-ui-part-2-430de537ba96

Erik is an independent UX and UI designer.  His clients range from funded startups to Fortune 100, and include Amazon, Soylent, and more.  He's also spoken in the US and abroad at conferences, universities, and businesses.  In a past life, he was a developer, and approaches design with a very analytical, no-BS mindset.  A million people have heard or read him blabber on about design.

Bring your questions this is going to be a great talk.

name: A Different Kind of Code: Forming an LLC & Other Legal Considerations
description:
This week's lunch is brought to you by EPB. 

In this talk, April Holland, a corporate attorney with Miller & Martin PLLC, will discuss two legal topics of relevance to the developer world.


Forming a single-member LLC - For those developers who have been freelancing as a sole proprietorship (i.e., you do not pay the state a franchise and excise tax for your business) you should consider forming a single-member LLC to protect your personal assets.  April will walk you through the steps of forming a single-member LLC on your own without the need for Legal Zoom or hiring an expensive law firm.  For those who have already formed your LLC, April will also share best practices related to business records upkeep.

Services Agreements – As developers, you may do work for clients based on an initial proposal, an engagement letter, statement of work, or even by a hand-shake agreement.  It is important to have a written document that summarizes the responsibilities and expectations of the work arrangement as well as outlining ownership of work product.  April will take you through a basic form of services agreement for developers to use with their clients and explain the most important terms for you to consider. 

You will leave this talk empowered with nuggets of legal knowledge and a basic services agreement that you can adapt and tweak for your own use.

April Holland helps companies with virtually every aspect of their corporate needs outside of the court room.  Her practice focuses on mergers and acquisitions for privately-held and publicly-traded companies, securities and franchise regulatory matters, fund formation, and contract review and negotiation.   She has assisted clients in a range of industries including technology, healthcare, flooring, transportation, insurance and bottling.  She is a regular guest speaker at LAUNCH Chattanooga Adult Entrepreneurship Academy classes.

name: The modern Salesforce development workflow w/ Visual Studio Code w/ John Nelson
description:
Shout out to EPB for sponsoring this week's lunch. Now for speaker details.

The modern Salesforce development workflow with Visual Studio Code will discuss what Salesforce is why it’s the top cloud platform for business. With this greatness comes compromises, and while it’s a great platform for business, this talk will cover the pain behind developing JavaScript SPAs with Salesforce and how using a modern workflow with Visual Studio Code can alleviate that pain.   Along the way, we will define what Visual Studio Code actually is and where it fits in with the modern workflow along with what technologies are used to enable that workflow.


John Nelson is a developer at CodeScience here in Chattanooga.  CodeScience is an ISV for the Salesforce platform that works with companies from many industries to make their Salesforce App wishes a reality.  CodeScience loves modern technologies, agile methodologies, and pushing the boundaries of what is possible on the Salesforce platform.

name: Building websites with Jekyll w/ Rodger Maarfi
description:
This weeks lunch is brought to you by Open Table.

Now for a word from our presenter, Rodger:

If you’ve ever wondered why you need a database just to deliver some html, Jekyll is worth taking a look at. Jekyll lets you generate static pages, and it’s “blog aware”.  Jekyll is written in ruby, though only minimal knowledge of ruby is required to work with it.

http://jekyllrb.com/

I’m a full stack ruby on rails developer who loves javascript. Client side MVC advocate; game and economics enthusiast. Currently the CTO of Woople.

name: Find Your Story: Build Better Sites by Building Better Stories w/ Andrew Steele
description:
This week's talk is brought to you by Lamp Post Group.

As developers, we sometimes forget that real people are going to be using our apps. In this talk, Andrew Steele - a Front End Engineer, UX Enthusiast, and Writer - will guide site and app creators in the importance of telling a story with their products. Looking at empathy, user stories, and infusing personality and creativity into something as small as a single button, listeners will walk away with practical advice and tools to make the web human again, one interface at a time.

name: The Internet 2.0, or how I learned to stop worrying and love the tubes
description:
Andrew Rodgers has been working with advanced research networks for several years, and is going to share what innovations might be gained from these experimental platforms. Along the way he'll touch on how the Internet works, how it grew into what it is today, and how it might be improved in the future.

"What Andrew lacks in knowledge, he makes up for with excessive boorish slides." - an internet expert (Ted Stevens)

name: Making Decisions with Cost Functions w/ River Kanies
description:
If you’re not sure what cost functions are and why they matter join us for this talk. If you do, River will be covering ground to keep you engaged as well.

Now a quick word from River:

=======

Cost functions are everywhere. All website optimizations make use of cost functions (it’s the thing you want to minimize). All neural nets are trained using cost function optimization: Siri, Google Search, and IBM Watson. But cost functions aren’t only found in software. Every decision you make is a miniature cost function optimization; that is, a process of weighing and scoring options (and the acting on the “best” option based on your assumptions).

=======

Look forward to seeing all of you on Thursday.

~ Brett

name: Let's Brainstorm Speaking Topics w/ Jessica Ivins
description:
Join us to brainstorm public speaking topics. At the end of the workshop, you’ll have a few topics that you’re confident about and excited about. 

You can give a Chadev lunch presentation on one of these topics, or you can give a talk at another event. 

Are you interested in public speaking, but you’re not sure what to speak about? Join us! Are you deathly afraid of public speaking and thinking, “%$#& no! I don’t want to speak publicly!” Join us anyway. We may just motivate you to overcome your fear of public speaking.

name: OCaml: An Introduction w/ Josh Marlow
description:
Join Josh Marlow (an enthusiastic novice at functional programming) for an introduction to the OCaml programming language.  OCaml is a functional language that also allows more common imperative coding.  This makes OCaml a great language to jump in and begin experimenting with functional programming.

If you’re not sure why you should care about functional languages or what they even are this will be a great talk for you too. Josh’s talk will include a high level overview of the basic concepts as well as digging into the application of those concepts in OCaml.
venue_name: Floor 5 at The Edney Innovation Center

name: Test for Security; Test for Design w/ Chris Keathley
description:
Chris will be talking to us about testing for the purpose of designing systems instead of regressions. 

In this talk he'll discuss tools and techniques to drive better designs with tests. Specifically he'll talk about test isolation with mocks and stubs, test speed, designing APIs, and more. Everyone will leave with a better understanding of how to utilize TDD and BDD to create not just safer code, but better code.
venue_name: Floor 5 at The Edney Innovation Center

name: Reactive Connected Clients with Meteor w/ James Holland
description:
The Talk

If you're not familiar with Meteor, or if you checked it out some time ago this will be a great talk for you. James will explore some of the basic "magic" of meteor, why he uses it over other frameworks out there and look at core concepts such as latency compensation, pub/sub, reactive templates, minimongo, and the optimistic UI.  He'll also walk through the setup of a basic Meteor app and share some opinionated experience to make things faster for you.  For a primer, check out this video by MDG founder Geoff Schmidt: (http://info.meteor.com/blog/javascript-state-of-the-union-with-meteor)

Meteor.js Background

Development of Meteor.js, a node.js based server/client javascript platform, began in 2011. It hit 1.0 in October 2014 and reached1.2 in September 2015. Development is driven by the Meteor Development Group which is funded by a number of prominent VC firms and a global open-source community. Meteor makes real-time websocket app connectivity seamless, has a baked-in reactive UI, uses MongoDB, and recently added core support for React, Angular, and SQL. 


About James

James Holland is a developer working in the Midnight Oil Refinery, building web apps in Meteor for B2B projects in niche industries such as textile manufacturing and regulatory law.  When not developing, he and his wife enjoy life in and around Chattanooga Southside.
venue_name: Floor 5 at The Edney Innovation Center

name: AARP & Tech Discussion Panel
description:
The AARP is making a visit to Chattanooga to learn about the Innovation District and the various policy changes that made it possible. During their visit we will be hosting a discussion panel.

There are many barriers that still exist when it comes to the 55+ population and technological adoption. This discussion panel will explore those barriers and also talk about what can be done and what's being done to remove them.

Our panel will be moderated by Ann Coulter. 

Panelists will include:

Stuart Dickerson, Unum, Senior Software Developer
Leslie Jensen-Inman, Center Centre, Co-founder
Dorothy Siemon, VP of Policy Integration, AARP
venue_name: Floor 5 at The Edney Innovation Center
